  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law in the United States, money laundering is a serious offense with significant penalties. The specific penalties can vary depending on the circumstances of the case, but generally include the following:\n\n### Criminal Penalties:\n1. **Imprisonment**: \n   - **Up to 20 years** for each money laundering offense under **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956** (which involves transactions designed to conceal the source of funds, promote illegal activity, or evade taxes).\n   - **Up to 10 years** for each offense under **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957** (which involves engaging in monetary transactions with criminally derived property of more than $10,000).\n\n2. **Fines**:\n   - Fines can be substantial, often up to **$500,000** or **twice the value of the property involved in the transaction**, whichever is greater.\n\n### Civil Penalties:\n1. **Forfeiture**:\n   - The government may seize and **forfeit** any property involved in the money laundering offense, including funds, assets, and other property derived from or traceable to the illegal activity.\n\n2. **Monetary Penalties**:\n   - Civil money penalties can also be imposed, which may include fines up to **$10,000** or **the value of the property involved**, whichever is greater.\n\n### Additional Consequences:\n1. **Enhanced Sentencing**:\n   - If the money laundering is connected to certain underlying crimes (such as drug trafficking or terrorism), the penalties can be more severe, including **life imprisonment** in some cases.\n\n2. **Collateral Consequences**:\n   - Conviction for money laundering can lead to additional consequences, such as loss of professional licenses, difficulty in obtaining future employment, and damage to personal and professional reputation.\n\n### Specific Statutes:\n- **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956**: Prohibits laundering of monetary instruments, with penalties of up to 20 years in prison and/or fines.\n- **18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1957**: Prohibits engaging in monetary transactions in criminally derived property, with penalties of up to 10 years in prison and/or fines.\n- **31 U.S.C. \u00a7 5322**: Provides for criminal penalties for certain violations of the Bank Secrecy Act, which includes failure to report transactions that may involve money laundering.\n\n### Examples of Penalties in Practice:\n- **Case Example**: In 2018, a former Venezuelan government official was sentenced to **10 years in prison** and ordered to **forfeit $1.2 billion** for his role in a money laundering scheme involving bribery and embezzlement.\n\n### Summary:\nThe penalties for money laundering under federal law are severe and can include lengthy prison sentences, substantial fines, and forfeiture of assets. The exact penalties depend on the specific circumstances of the case, including the amount of money involved, the nature of the underlying criminal activity, and the defendant\u2019s role in the scheme.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
